<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-190-078 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 376 651</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  April 1991 v8 n4 p144(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The electronic palette: 11 color paint and 2 photo-editingprograms cross brushes. (includes related articles on comparisonbetween ColorStudio and Adobe Photoshop, Time Arts' Oasis package)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McClelland, Deke.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A guide to color painting and image-editing programs is presented.andO;True-color 24-bit systems are expensive but indispensable forserious graphic artists.andP;  Only Electronic Arts' Studio/32implements virtual memory to let users edit images larger in sizethan the available RAM, making large amounts of memory anecessity.andP;  Studio/32, Delta Two Software's Color MacCheese andDeskPaint from Zedcor let users access 24-bit color with an 8-bitsystem via automatic dithering simulations.andP;  Color paint programsgenerally print only bit-mapped text, but Adobe Type Manager and'antialiasing' features built into some packages can product veryreadable large type.andP;  Many packages provide unique tools forspecial effects.andP;  Color MacCheese and Easy Color Paint areexceptional deals for the casual user; Studio/32 and PixelPaintProfessional are good choices among high-end packages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     ColorGraphics SoftwareDirectoriesGraphic arts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>